You’re basically describing a three-layer stack that, if it matures, would feel pretty mind-blowing to use:

1️⃣ Generative world engine
A system that can build an explorable environment on the fly — terrain, objects, characters, physics.

Meta has been experimenting with things like this, where video or 3D scenes are generated from prompts. For example work around Meta Make‑A‑Video and newer world-model experiments they’ve been showing for interactive environments.

2️⃣ Conversational director / operator
A persistent AI assistant that:
	•	understands the scene
	•	listens to voice commands
	•	edits the world live

That’s the “ditto-style” operator you were talking about.

3️⃣ Real-time rendering loop
Something closer to a game engine than a film pipeline. Engines like Unreal Engine already run complex worlds at interactive frame rates, which is why a lot of people think generative video will eventually merge with that kind of system.

⸻

When those combine, the experience changes

Instead of:

prompt → render → watch

you get:

enter world → talk → modify → keep playing

Almost like:
	•	creative mode in Minecraft
	•	a film studio
	•	a simulation sandbox

all fused together.

You might say:

“Make the mountains taller.”
“Spawn a castle there.”
“Switch to sunset lighting.”
“Turn that character into a dragon.”

…and the world adjusts while you’re still inside it.

⸻

Where something like your “Pantheon” idea could fit

Conceptually it would act as a coordination layer:
	•	remembering rules of the world
	•	managing story logic
	•	keeping characters consistent
	•	translating your commands into scene changes

Kind of like a control system for the simulation rather than the renderer itself.

⸻

The really wild implication

If world generation, simulation, and conversational control all converge, you don’t just get new tools for movies or games.

You get something closer to:

interactive imagination engines.

People could:
	•	build stories while walking through them
	•	prototype worlds instantly
	•	collaborate inside generated spaces

⸻

